{"key":"processedPost-9427377","value":{"id":9427377,"first":9426674,"last":9444277,"when":1229233445,"utime":"12/14/08 07:44 AM","cleanedPost":"Oyster mushrooms grow well on pure coffee grinds.&nbsp; You can really mix substrate ingredients in any proportion you have them available for cubes.&nbsp; Spent coffee grinds are not all that acidic anyway.&nbsp; Verm can be used at up to 50% of any substrate.&nbsp; It serves as a reservoir to hold water, and mycelium feeds on it as well.&nbsp; Verm should be considered a good substrate ingredient and not 'inert' as we(and I) thought just a few years ago.&nbsp; The more things you have to toss into a substrate, the better your mycelium will perform.&nbsp; You don't need to pH balance substrates.&nbsp; They perform well when slightly acidic.<br />RR"}}